This paper deals with network coding and information theory, which are both subfields of computer science. The paper focuses on approximating the sum-rate of multiple-unicasts, which is a problem in information theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also deals with network coding, which involves designing efficient algorithms for transmitting data over networks. This makes cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also involves establishing separation results for vector-linear network codes, which is a problem in theoretical computer science. This makes cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity) likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves analyzing the impact of the choice of field on the performance of a linear network code, which is a problem in computer systems. This makes cs.SI (Systems and Control) a likely sub-category as well.
